## Revised Timeline Suggestion (17 weeks)

| Phase | Tasks | Duration |
|---|---|---|
| Literature review | Simulator design literature, gaze feature literature, updated reward shaping | 2 weeks |
| Simulator analysis | Document current SM limitations, design improvement ladder | 1 week |
| Implementation | SM-v2 through SM-v4, reward changes, multi-feature gaze | 4 weeks |
| Experiments | Simulator ladder × reward conditions, gaze feature comparison | 3 weeks |
| Analysis & writing | Results, discussion, thesis draft | 5 weeks |
| Revision & submission | Supervisor feedback, final version | 2 weeks |

---

## Key Risks & Mitigations

| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Simulator improvements don't change agent behaviour | High | Start with the dwell-range fix — this is almost guaranteed to have an effect since the current ranges overlap for 5/9 states |
| Too many variables to test (simulator × reward × gaze) | Medium | Prioritise simulator improvements; use reward and gaze as secondary axes |
| Multi-feature gaze is meaningless if features are derived from dwell | Medium | Redesign gaze feature generation *first*, before running comparison experiments |
| Scope creep: 3 pillars is ambitious for a master's thesis | Medium | Pillar 2 is the thesis. Pillars 1 and 3 are supporting contributions that strengthen the story. |

---

## Summary Recommendation

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The revised direction is better than the original.** The shift from "reward function is the problem" to "simulator quality is the bottleneck" is well-supported by Daniel's own evidence. The three-pillar structure gives you depth (Pillar 2) with breadth (Pillars 1, 3), and every pillar produces concrete, measurable results.
>
> The original proposal risked building elaborate reward mathematics only to find that the simulator can't provide the signal quality needed to test them — exactly the problem Daniel ran into. The revised direction attacks the simulator first, then uses reward improvements and gaze features to amplify whatever gains the simulator improvements produce.

My one strong suggestion: **Make the dwell-range overlap fix your first implementation task.** It's a concrete bug/limitation in the current code, it directly undermines the "non-overlapping signals" claim in Daniel's thesis, and fixing it will give you immediate experimental results to validate the approach.
